nib.text:
April 15 is the day of Minnesota’s statewide tornado drill. Hennepin County and Ramsey County will participate by sounding outdoor warning sirens twice, once at 1:45 p.m. for those in schools or businesses and a second time at 6:45 p.m. for families.

The drills are part of Minnesota Severe Weather Awareness Week. In Hennepin County, nearly two-thirds of federally declared disasters have been due to tornadoes and other severe weather since 1960. This week serves as a reminder to create, update, and practice household and workplace emergency plans.

Sirens alert people who are outdoors of severe weather warnings and other dangerous situations that threaten their safety. Those who are indoors may not hear the sirens and instead should rely on another means to get warnings, such as a NOAA weather radio and local television or radio stations.

-MYIwvnywfaRzMUdW28e.text: During a press conference, Col. Matt Langer of the Minnesota State Patrol stated 24 people have been arrested.

-MYIxf3nEvHEeS7OcRG-.text: According to Deputy Chief Amelia Huffman of the MPD, there were no reports of burglary or looting.

nib.text:
Protesters gathered outside of the Brooklyn Center Police Department for a fourth night following the shooting death of Daunte Wright.

User footage captured from within the crowd showcased the tense situation between police and protesters. 

According to officials with Operation Safety Net (OSN), objects were thrown at law enforcement and some people were trying to climb the fence around the building. Police responded by deploying chemical irritants into the crowd.

The gathering was declared an unlawful assembly around 9 p.m. Police began to issue dispersal orders.

Additional Minnesota National Guard and Minnesota State Patrol officers arrived in the area as the 10 p.m. curfew was going into effect.

Officials say that demonstrators constructed makeshift barricades with scrap wood and umbrellas. 

In a midnight press conference, officials say that they made 24 arrests relating to Wednesday night's protests.

-MYDTj39O9gRPp7c2Sw4.text: An officer stated that he was shot at south of the scene at the Brooklyn Center Police Department. UPDATE: Officials have not confirmed if any shots were fired during the protests.

nib.text:
Police made upwards of 60 arrests after the 10:00 p.m. curfew went into effect in Brooklyn Center Tuesday night, police said.

Earlier in the evening, a "Justice for Daunte Wright" rally was held. 

The group marched to the FBI building in Brooklyn Center and then back to the police department in the third night of protests since Daunte Wright was fatally shot by a former Brooklyn Center police officer during a traffic stop.

According to officials, demonstrators aimed fireworks and laser pointers, causing police to issue an order to disperse.

Police say some demonstrators began to throw debris at officers. 

At least 60 people were arrested in Brooklyn Center, for behavior described by a state police spokesperson as riotous and criminal. They were to be booked at Hennepin County jail on various charges.

In Minneapolis, two arrests were made for curfew violations.

There were no reports of looting in Minneapolis Tuesday night.
